{
  "text": "RP-HPLC offers higher sensitivity, versatility, and speed of analysis than classical ion-exchange separations [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The more usual methods involve precolumn derivatization with phenylisothiocyanate (PITC) [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] or o-phthalaldehyde (OPA) [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Although OPA methods show a higher sensitivity and more suitable features for automation than PITC methods, OPA derivatives are highly unstable, and direct detection of secondary amino acids (proline and hydroxyproline) and sulfur amino acids (cysteine and homocysteine) is not possible [CITATION_7] . OPA methods have been recommended for quantification of primary amino acids in physiological fluids, whereas PITC methods have been proposed when both primary and secondary amino acids are to be determined [CITATION_8] .",
  "correct_citation": {
